<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-07-18T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-07-18T04:00:00-05:00" n="94" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">711.9412Anti-War/48: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Neville</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-07-18T18:00:00+09:00"><hi rend="italic">July 18,
                                            1928—6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received July 18—8:48
                                    a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>86. My telegram No. 83, July 9, 2 p.m.<note n="99" xml:id="d94fn99">Not printed.</note> Foreign Minister told me today that the
                                question of wording is still causing some difficulty in the
                                Government. He said that this is the only reason for Japanese
                                Parliament’s delay in answering, but he hoped to be able to reply
                                favorably in a few days.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Neville</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>